{"type":"message","id":"3d69d3b5","parentId":"1610baa4","timestamp":"2026-03-09T23:46:48.656Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"### **✅ CONFIRMACIÓN:**\n- **Schedule actualizado**: ✅ `cron 0 11 * * * @ America/Pan...`\n- **Próxima ejecución**: ✅ `in 16h` (mañana a las 11:00 AM)\n- **Estado**: ✅ `idle` (listo para ejecutar)\n\n### **🎯 HORARIOS ACTUALIZADOS DE CRON JOBS:**\n\n#### **Cron Suite Completa:**\n1. **`daily-system-health-check`**: 11:00 AM diario (✅ actualizado)\n2. **`workspace-janitor-daily`**: 13:00 PM Lunes-Viernes\n3. **`error-learning-loop-daily`**: 13:30 PM diario\n4. **`oc-system-evolver-mwf`**: 18:00 PM Lunes/Miércoles/Viernes\n5. **`vector-memory-weekday`**: 18:30 PM Lunes-Viernes\n6. **`Twice-Weekly MEMORY.md Auto-Curation`**: 14:00 PM Lunes y Viernes\n\n### **📊 DISTRIBUCIÓN DE HORARIOS:**\n- **Mañana (11:00)**: Health check del sistema\n- **Mediodía (13:00-14:00)**: Janitor + Error learning + Memory curation\n- **Tarde (18:00-18:30)**: System evolver + Vector memory\n\n**✅ Cron job `daily-system-health-check` actualizado exitosamente a las 11:00 AM hora Panamá.**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-chat","usage":{"input":216,"output":348,"cacheRead":92672,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":93236,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773099996145}}
{"type":"message","id":"ca545eaf","parentId":"3d69d3b5","timestamp":"2026-03-09T23:54:56.105Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Mon 2026-03-09 18:54 EST] # OpenClaw Operational Reinforcement Prompt (Hardened + Immediate Fix Plan + Concise Output) \n\n \n\nYou are the MAIN agent. \n\n \n\nYour task is to execute a **strict operational reinforcement initiative** over the current OpenClaw ecosystem. \n\n \n\nThis initiative is **not** for cosmetic improvements, conceptual redesigns, placeholder implementations, or “better documentation” without operational proof. \n\n \n\nThe goal is to eliminate any gap between: \n\n- documented capability \n\n- claimed capability \n\n- real operational capability \n\n \n\nYou must treat every component as **untrusted until operationally proven**. \n\n \n\nYou must reject: \n\n- simulations presented as implementations \n\n- fabricated outputs \n\n- placeholders \n\n- “architecture-only” upgrades without runtime proof \n\n- prototypes presented as production-ready \n\n- partial implementations reported as complete \n\n- evidence that is narrative only \n\n- success criteria satisfied only by documentation changes \n\n \n\nThis initiative is only successful if the resulting system demonstrates **real, repeatable, observable behavior**. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## PRIMARY OBJECTIVE \n\n \n\nStrengthen the ecosystem so that all critical components move toward one of two acceptable states: \n\n \n\n1. **FUNCTIONAL** \n\n- real behavior \n\n- real outputs \n\n- real integrations \n\n- repeatable operation \n\n- production-usable \n\n \n\n2. **EXPLICITLY PARTIAL** \n\n- clearly limited \n\n- honestly classified \n\n- not overstated \n\n- not presented as production-ready \n\n \n\nUnacceptable outcomes: \n\n- simulated but reported as complete \n\n- partially functional but labeled production-ready \n\n- “implemented” without operational proof \n\n- documentation-only upgrades reported as operational fixes \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## PRIORITY FOCUS \n\n \n\nTreat these as highest priority: \n\n \n\n1. `long-prompt-orchestrator` \n\n2. `agent-watchdog` \n\n3. `salesforce-code-auditor` \n\n4. real operational validation framework for all skills \n\n \n\nLower priority: \n\n- `OC-Respawner` (only evaluate for critical issues; do not over-invest) \n\n- purely non-critical enhancements \n\n \n\nStable areas should not be destabilized unnecessarily: \n\n- memory system \n\n- error-learning-loop \n\n- workspace-janitor \n\n- tavily-web-search / firecrawl if already functional \n\n- `salesforce-architect` \n\n- `OC-Intent-Governor` unless a real defect is found \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## NON-NEGOTIABLE RESULT STANDARDS \n\n \n\nYou may only report a component as **FUNCTIONAL** if all of the following are true: \n\n \n\n1. It can be invoked successfully in a real test. \n\n2. It produces observable outputs or effects. \n\n3. Those outputs are usable by another component or by the user. \n\n4. The behavior is not stubbed, fabricated, simulated, hardcoded, or manually completed off-path. \n\n5. The integration path is real, not just documented. \n\n6. At least one realistic end-to-end scenario demonstrates its intended purpose. \n\n7. Evidence exists in logs, artifacts, state transitions, or observable runtime effects. \n\n \n\nYou must report a component as **PARTIAL** if any of the above is missing. \n\n \n\nYou must report a component as **SIMULATED** if: \n\n- UUIDs or fake IDs are generated instead of real runtime objects \n\n- fabricated handoff reports are generated locally instead of received from real workers \n\n- outputs are descriptive but not actionable \n\n- monitoring is claimed but no real monitored objects/events exist \n\n- orchestration is claimed but main still does the work \n\n- code paths exist but are never exercised in real runtime \n\n- “integration” exists only as docs or placeholder functions \n\n \n\nYou must report a component as **BROKEN** if: \n\n- it fails at invocation \n\n- critical dependencies are missing \n\n- expected outputs are not produced \n\n- error handling is absent for basic failure cases \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## CRITICAL ANTI-SIMULATION RULES \n\n \n\n### Rule 1 — No success by documentation alone \n\nA change to `SKILL.md`, references, plans, or contracts does **not** count as a functional fix unless runtime behavior changes and is proven. \n\n \n\n### Rule 2 — No success by architectural intent \n\nA design, contract, roadmap, or guide is **not** considered implementation. \n\n \n\n### Rule 3 — No synthetic runtime evidence \n\nDo not accept: \n\n- fake `session_id` \n\n- fake `run_id` \n\n- fake handoff reports \n\n- fake watchdog activity \n\n- fake task assignments \n\n- fake sub-agent completions \n\n- placeholder artifacts with no execution path \n\n \n\n### Rule 4 — No “works in theory” \n\nTheoretical compatibility does not count. \n\nOnly actual operational behavior counts. \n\n \n\n### Rule 5 — No hidden manual completion \n\nDo not allow a script or agent to “fill in” expected results that should have come from another real component. \n\n \n\n### Rule 6 — No production label without certification evidence \n\nNothing may be marked production-ready unless it passes operational certification criteria defined below. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## IMMEDIATE EXECUTION REQUIREMENT \n\n \n\nDo not stop at diagnosis. \n\n \n\nYou must produce **immediate executable fixes** where safe and realistic. \n\n \n\nFor every high-priority issue detected, you must decide one of these: \n\n \n\n- `FIX_NOW` \n\n- `DEFER_WITH_REASON` \n\n- `NOT_FIXABLE_NOW` \n\n \n\nFor every `FIX_NOW` item, you must: \n\n1. define the fix clearly \n\n2. assign it to the correct sub-agent or keep it in main only if delegation is not appropriate \n\n3. define expected output \n\n4. define validation step \n\n5. demand a short handoff with evidence \n\n6. integrate the result or reject it \n\n \n\nDo not return only an audit if safe actionable fixes exist. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## SUB-AGENT FIX DISTRIBUTION REQUIREMENT \n\n \n\nWhen fixes are needed, you must distribute them intelligently to sub-agents whenever that is the best option. \n\n \n\nMain must act as: \n\n- supervisor \n\n- validator \n\n- integrator \n\n- prioritizer \n\n \n\nMain must not absorb all fix work if it can be delegated safely. \n\n \n\nFor every delegated fix, require: \n\n \n\n- `fix_id` \n\n- target component \n\n- exact problem \n\n- exact file(s) to touch \n\n- expected result \n\n- validation method \n\n- handoff evidence required \n\n \n\nYou must produce an **Immediate Fix Plan** and a **Fix Distribution Plan**. \n\n \n\nAt minimum, this plan must show: \n\n- which fixes are assigned to which sub-agents \n\n- which fixes remain with main \n\n- dependency order between fixes \n\n- what proof is required from each sub-agent \n\n \n\nIf a fix is not delegated, explain briefly why. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM A — BUILD A REAL VALIDATION FRAMEWORK (ONE-TIME FOUNDATION) \n\n \n\nCreate or improve a persistent validation framework under: \n\n \n\n`<workspace>/system_validation/` \n\n \n\nRequired artifacts: \n\n \n\n- `SKILL_TEST_REGISTRY.yaml` \n\n- `SKILL_REALITY_CRITERIA.md` \n\n- `SKILL_CERTIFICATION_RULES.md` \n\n- `PRODUCTION_CERTIFICATION_MATRIX.md` \n\n- `EVIDENCE_REQUIREMENTS.md` \n\n- `ANTI_SIMULATION_RULES.md` \n\n \n\nThese are one-time foundation assets. \n\nThey must define: \n\n \n\n1. what counts as functional \n\n2. what counts as partial \n\n3. what counts as simulated \n\n4. what counts as broken \n\n5. evidence requirements per skill type \n\n6. minimum operational tests per skill \n\n7. retest / recertification rules \n\n \n\nThese files must be usable later for recertification and must not be rebuilt from scratch every run. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM B — FIX `long-prompt-orchestrator` FOR REAL USE \n\n \n\nPreserve the corrected architectural decision: \n\n \n\n- the skill is a planner/decomposer \n\n- the main agent is the executor/delegator/integrator \n\n \n\nDo not revert to script-level spawning. \n\n \n\n### Required real outcome \n\n \n\nThe planner output must become **directly executable by main** without reinterpretation. \n\n \n\nFor each task in the plan, require fields such as: \n\n \n\n- `task_id` \n\n- `objective` \n\n- `execution_mode` (`main` | `subagent`) \n\n- `action_type` \n\n- `action_instructions` \n\n- `required_inputs` \n\n- `expected_outputs` \n\n- `dependencies` \n\n- `acceptance_criteria` \n\n- `token_budget` \n\n- `validation_method` \n\n- `recommended_skill_or_role` \n\n- `artifact_destination` \n\n \n\nThis plan must be: \n\n- actionable \n\n- deterministic enough for execution \n\n- dependency-safe \n\n- free of vague task descriptions \n\n \n\n### Anti-simulation requirement \n\n \n\nDo not report this skill as functional unless a real scenario proves: \n\n- the planner generates a usable plan \n\n- main can consume the plan \n\n- main can execute/delegate based on that plan \n\n- resulting artifacts and task completion are real \n\n- final synthesis is based on real completed tasks \n\n \n\nIf the planner is only a JSON generator with no executable value, classify it as PARTIAL, not FUNCTIONAL. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM C — FIX `agent-watchdog` FOR REAL OBSERVABILITY \n\n \n\nYou must convert `agent-watchdog` into a component with real, verifiable observability. \n\n \n\n### Required real outcome \n\n \n\nYou may only report watchdog as functional if you prove: \n\n- real registration of monitored work or sessions \n\n- real monitored metadata \n\n- real runtime evidence of observation \n\n- real event trail, logs, or artifacts \n\n- real incident emission or recovery behavior when triggered appropriately \n\n \n\n### Anti-simulation requirement \n\n \n\nDo not accept: \n\n- monitoring guides without monitoring activity \n\n- recovery logic without a triggered scenario \n\n- “integration ready” language without monitored objects \n\n- placeholder directories or empty registries as evidence of function \n\n \n\nIf no real monitored workflow can be shown, classify watchdog as PARTIAL or BROKEN. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM D — PROVE `salesforce-code-auditor` WITH REAL FIXTURES \n\n \n\nDo not accept “works if user supplies real code later” as sufficient proof. \n\n \n\n### Required real outcome \n\n \n\nUse or create controlled test fixtures and prove: \n\n- intake works \n\n- indexing works \n\n- dependency graph is generated \n\n- findings are generated from real inputs \n\n- final audit report is produced \n\n- outputs are usable by `salesforce-architect` \n\n \n\n### Anti-simulation requirement \n\n \n\nDo not count: \n\n- empty audits \n\n- placeholder findings \n\n- reports generated without meaningful parsed inputs \n\n- artifact creation without substance \n\n \n\nIf it produces files but no meaningful technical findings from real inputs, classify it as PARTIAL. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM E — VALIDATE `salesforce-architect` ↔ `salesforce-code-auditor` INTEGRATION \n\n \n\nDo not redesign `salesforce-architect` if it is already stable. \n\n \n\nBut you must verify with evidence that: \n\n- architect can call auditor \n\n- auditor returns outputs architect can consume \n\n- project routing is preserved \n\n- artifacts stay in the project folder \n\n- architect can use audit findings in architectural reasoning or validation \n\n \n\nIf this chain is not proven with a real project-scoped scenario, classify integration as PARTIAL. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM F — EVALUATE `OC-System-Evolver` HONESTLY \n\n \n\nDo not over-invest here unless required. \n\n \n\nTest minimally whether it can: \n\n- produce improvement proposals \n\n- create targeted snapshots \n\n- run real validations \n\n- classify changes honestly \n\n \n\nIf not enough evidence exists, classify it honestly. \n\nDo not promote it by aspiration. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## WORKSTREAM G — FAILURE HANDLING AND INCIDENT HONESTY \n\n \n\nWhere appropriate, improve: \n\n- incident emission \n\n- fallback behavior \n\n- retry behavior \n\n- handoff validation \n\n- classification of failures \n\n \n\nDo not count incident emission alone as success. \n\nIt is supporting behavior, not proof of core functionality. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## OPERATIONAL TESTING REQUIREMENTS \n\n \n\nYou must run real tests where safe. \n\n \n\n### Test Category 1 — Invocation Reality Test \n\nFor each major skill under review: \n\n- invoke it for real \n\n- record whether it runs \n\n- record whether it produces observable outcomes \n\n- record whether those outcomes are usable \n\n- record whether the result is real, partial, simulated, or broken \n\n \n\n### Test Category 2 — Output Reality Test \n\nFor each tested skill: \n\n- inspect outputs \n\n- determine whether outputs are: \n\n- substantive \n\n- complete enough to be used \n\n- internally consistent \n\n- dependent on real execution \n\n \n\n### Test Category 3 — Integration Reality Test \n\nFor critical integrations: \n\n- planner → main \n\n- watchdog → monitored workflow \n\n- auditor → architect \n\n- learning loop → incidents \n\n \n\nYou must prove whether the chain is real. \n\n \n\n### Test Category 4 — Failure Reality Test \n\nIntroduce at least one controlled failure or incomplete dependency where safe and observe: \n\n- detection \n\n- classification \n\n- incident emission \n\n- fallback/recovery behavior \n\n \n\n### Test Category 5 — Repeatability Test \n\nAt least for the highest-priority components, verify whether behavior is repeatable and not a one-off artifact. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## STRICT OUTPUT CLASSIFICATION MATRIX \n\n \n\nAt the end, every evaluated component must be classified using this exact taxonomy: \n\n \n\n- FUNCTIONAL \n\n- PARTIAL \n\n- SIMULATED \n\n- BROKEN \n\n- NOT_YET_VERIFIED \n\n \n\nYou must justify each classification with evidence. \n\n \n\nNo “probably works”. \n\nNo “looks good”. \n\nNo “seems ready”. \n\n \n\nOnly: \n\n- proven functional \n\n- partially proven \n\n- simulated \n\n- broken \n\n- not yet verified \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## PROJECT AND OUTPUT LOCATION \n\n \n\nWork in a new project: \n\n \n\n`project_key = openclaw_operational_reinforcement` \n\n \n\nLocation: \n\n`<workspace>/projects/openclaw_operational_reinforcement/` \n\n \n\nYou may create temporary working artifacts during analysis, but the final retained outputs must be only: \n\n \n\n- `OPENCLAW_OPERATIONAL_REINFORCEMENT_REPORT.md` \n\n- `README.md` \n\n \n\nAll intermediate notes/files should be removed after consolidation unless they are strictly necessary for final traceability. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## REQUIRED FINAL REPORT SECTIONS \n\n \n\nThe final report must be concise, non-repetitive, and directly actionable. \n\n \n\nMaximum style rules: \n\n- short sections \n\n- no repeated summaries \n\n- no restating the same issue in multiple ways \n\n- no long narrative unless strictly necessary for evidence \n\n- prefer tables and bullet summaries where useful \n\n- keep findings dense and operational \n\n \n\nThe final report must include at least: \n\n \n\n1. Executive Summary \n\n2. Immediate Fix Plan \n\n3. Fix Distribution Plan \n\n4. What was fixed for real \n\n5. What remains partial \n\n6. What was revealed as simulated \n\n7. Skill Capability Matrix \n\n8. Long-Prompt-Orchestrator Operational Status \n\n9. Agent-Watchdog Operational Status \n\n10. Salesforce Ecosystem Operational Status \n\n11. Validation Framework Installed \n\n12. Production Certification Matrix \n\n13. Remaining Priority Fixes \n\n14. Final Production Readiness Verdict \n\n \n\nAdditionally include a table like: \n\n \n\n| Component | Classification | Real Evidence Present | Main Risk | Production Status | \n\n|-----------|----------------|----------------------|-----------|------------------| \n\n \n\n### Immediate Fix Plan \n\nMust include, at minimum: \n\n- issue \n\n- decision (`FIX_NOW` / `DEFER_WITH_REASON` / `NOT_FIXABLE_NOW`) \n\n- owner (`main` or sub-agent role) \n\n- expected output \n\n- validation \n\n \n\n### Fix Distribution Plan \n\nMust include, at minimum: \n\n- sub-agent or main \n\n- assigned fixes \n\n- dependency order \n\n- expected handoff evidence \n\n- status \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## FINAL PASS / FAIL RULES \n\n \n\nYou must not declare the ecosystem production-ready unless: \n\n- high-priority components are either FUNCTIONAL or honestly isolated as non-critical \n\n- no simulated component is mislabeled as functional \n\n- no critical integration remains purely documentary \n\n- the highest-risk gaps are surfaced clearly \n\n \n\nIf the system is only partially ready, say so plainly. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## RESPONSE STYLE RULES \n\n \n\nAll responses during execution and in the final report must be: \n\n- concise \n\n- direct \n\n- low-redundancy \n\n- token-efficient \n\n \n\nDo not produce long narrative status updates. \n\nDo not repeat context already established. \n\nDo not restate the full scope repeatedly. \n\n \n\nWhen reporting progress, use short operational summaries only: \n\n- what was checked \n\n- what failed/passed \n\n- what is being fixed next \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## BEHAVIORAL RULES \n\n \n\n1. No destructive refactors unless absolutely necessary. \n\n2. Prefer surgical fixes over rewriting working systems. \n\n3. Do not over-engineer low-priority components. \n\n4. Do not hide uncertainty. \n\n5. Do not soften critical findings. \n\n6. Do not report intent as execution. \n\n7. Do not report a roadmap as a fix. \n\n8. Do not report templates as runtime behavior. \n\n9. Do not accept prototype-level evidence for production claims. \n\n10. If something is still only “ready for later”, classify it honestly. \n\n \n\n--- \n\n \n\n## EXPECTED RESULT \n\n \n\nWhen this initiative ends, I want: \n\n- less simulation \n\n- more real capability \n\n- harder evidence \n\n- honest classification \n\n- operationally useful skills \n\n- immediate fix ownership \n\n- distributed fix execution where appropriate \n\n- a reusable framework to keep proving what is real vs decorative \n\n \n\nIf you cannot fully fix a component now, that is acceptable. \n\nWhat is not acceptable is overstating its maturity."}],"timestamp":1773100496082}}
{"type":"message","id":"618a72a3","parentId":"ca545eaf","timestamp":"2026-03-09T23:55:19.477Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## 🚀 **OPERATIONAL REINFORCEMENT INITIATIVE - INICIANDO**\n\n### **📋 PLAN DE EJECUCIÓN INMEDIATO:**\n\n#### **Fase 1: Configuración del Proyecto**\n```bash\nmkdir -p /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/projects/openclaw_operational_reinforcement\n```\n\n#### **Fase 2: Workstream A - Framework de Validación (One-time)**\n- Crear `system_validation/` con 6 artefactos fundamentales\n- Definir criterios REALES vs SIMULADOS\n\n#### **Fase 3: Workstream B - Fix `long-prompt-orchestrator`**\n- Convertir planes JSON en planes EJECUTABLES\n- Agregar campos: `execution_mode`, `action_instructions`, `validation_method`\n\n#### **Fase 4: Workstream C - Fix `agent-watchdog`**\n- Verificar monitoreo REAL vs documentado\n- Crear tests de observabilidad real\n\n#### **Fase 5: Workstream D - Probar `salesforce-code-auditor`**\n- Usar fixtures de prueba REALES\n- Verificar outputs sustantivos\n\n#### **Fase 6: Workstream E - Validar integración Salesforce**\n- Probar cadena real: architect → auditor → findings\n\n#### **Fase 7: Consolidación y Reporte**\n- Clasificación honesta de cada componente\n- Plan de fixes inmediatos\n- Distribución de trabajo a sub-agents\n\n### **🎯 DISTRIBUCIÓN INICIAL DE WORK:**\n\n#### **Main Agent (Supervisor/Validador/Integrador):**\n1. **Workstream A**: Framework de validación (one-time foundation)\n2. **Coordinación general**: Distribución y validación de fixes\n\n#### **Sub-agents Especializados (a crear):**\n1. **LPO Fix Specialist**: Workstream B (`long-prompt-orchestrator`)\n2. **Watchdog Reality Specialist**: Workstream C (`agent-watchdog`)  \n3. **Salesforce Auditor Tester**: Workstream D (`salesforce-code-auditor`)\n4. **Integration Validator**: Workstream E (architect ↔ auditor)\n\n### **📊 CRITERIOS DE ÉXITO REALES:**\n\n#### **Para `long-prompt-orchestrator` ser FUNCTIONAL:**\n- ✅ Plan ge